UID:f4f2aef9-be42-4e96-8384-e55157fd13fe@conf.researchr.org
CREATED:20260602T202002Z
SUMMARY:[PROMISE] Keynote 2 - Rethinking Reliability for Software Engineering Agents - Tse-Hsun (Peter) Chen
DESCRIPTION:Abstract\nSoftware engineering agents are increasingly used for long-horizon tasks that span dozens of reasoning steps\, such as understanding issues\, searching repositories\, editing code\, and running tools. In these settings\, reliability depends not only on the final outcome but on the entire sequence of decisions the agent makes along the way.\nThis talk rethinks reliability for SE agents from the perspective of agent trajectories. Raw execution logs are difficult to reuse\, diagnose\, and verify. To make agents reliable\, we need trajectory representations that capture the structure of agent behavior: what the agent tried\, where it went wrong\, and whether the final outcome should be trusted. I will discuss how trajectory structure can help agents learn from prior experience\, how trajectory analysis can identify the origins of failures\, and how stronger validation can distinguish real success from plausible but incorrect results. I argue that building this reliability loop is a problem the SE community is uniquely positioned to own.\nSpeaker Bio\nTse-Hsun (Peter) Chen is an Associate Professor at Concordia University in Montreal\, Canada\, where he leads the Software Performance\, Analysis\, and Reliability (SPEAR) Lab. His research focuses on the intersection of software engineering and AI agents. He received his BSc from the University of British Columbia and his MSc and PhD from Queen’s University. His work has been published in flagship venues\, including AAAI\, ACL\, ASE\, ICSE\, ICML\, and FSE. He received the prestigious CS-CAN/INFO-CAN Outstanding Early Career Computer Science Researcher Award and is recognized as one of the most active early-career researchers in software engineering worldwide. In addition to his academic career\, Dr. Chen worked as a software performance engineer at BlackBerry for over four years and as an applied AI researcher/consultant for Ericsson. Early tools developed by Dr. Chen were integrated into industrial practice to ensure the quality of large-scale enterprise systems.\n
LOCATION:MB 3.430 - 1450 Guy St, Montreal, Quebec H3H 0A1, Montreal, Canada
LAST-MODIFIED:20260614T214533Z
END:VEVENT
BEGIN:VEVENT
DTSTART:20260705T190000Z
DTEND:20260705T191500Z
DTSTAMP:20260625T155151Z
UID:dddabc5c-9359-4eeb-ae9b-14d5d3f5f78d@conf.researchr.org
CREATED:20260602T202002Z
SUMMARY:[PROMISE] Beyond Code Snippets: Benchmarking LLMs on Repository-Level Question Answering - Yoseph Berhanu Alebachew\, Hunter Leary\, Swanand Vaishampayan\, Chris Brown
DESCRIPTION:Large Language Models (LLMs) have shown impressive capabilities across software engineering tasks\, including question answering (QA). However\, most studies and benchmarks focus on isolated functions or single-file snippets\, overlooking the challenges of real-world program comprehension\, which often spans multiple files and system-level dependencies. In this work\, we introduce StackRepoQA\, the first multi-project\, repository-level question answering dataset constructed from 1\,318 real developer questions and accepted answers across 134 open-source Java projects. Using this dataset\, we systematically evaluate two widely used LLMs (Claude 3.5 Sonnet and GPT-4o) under both direct prompting and agentic configurations. We compare baseline performance with retrieval-augmented generation methods that leverage file-level retrieval and graph-based representations of structural dependencies. Our results show that LLMs achieve moderate accuracy at baseline\, with performance improving when structural signals are incorporated. Nonetheless\, overall accuracy remains limited for repository-scale comprehension. Analysis reveals that high scores often result from verbatim reproduction of Stack Overflow answers rather than genuine reasoning. To our knowledge\, this is the first empirical study to provide such evidence in repository-level QA.  We release StackRepoQA to encourage further research into benchmarks\, evaluation protocols\, and augmentation strategies that disentangle memorization from reasoning\, advancing LLMs as reliable tool for repository-scale program comprehension.\n
LOCATION:MB 3.430 - 1450 Guy St, Montreal, Quebec H3H 0A1, Montreal, Canada
LAST-MODIFIED:20260602T205637Z
END:VEVENT
BEGIN:VEVENT
DTSTART:20260705T191500Z
DTEND:20260705T193000Z
DTSTAMP:20260625T155151Z
UID:08fa959a-909a-4575-bc8e-6386bd3dc656@conf.researchr.org
CREATED:20260602T202002Z
SUMMARY:[PROMISE] Do LLMs Learn Structure or Names? A Study on the Robustness of Design-Pattern Detection to Identifier Shifts - Ichsan Budiman\, Leandro Minku
DESCRIPTION:Large Language Models (LLMs) have recently achieved strong results for automated object-oriented Design-Pattern Detection (DPD). However\, it remains unclear whether these gains come from learning pattern-defining structure (e.g.\, inheritance\, delegation\, object creation) or from exploiting identifier names (class\, method\, variable names) and pattern annotations. This distinction matters in practice as names are often incomplete\, misleading\, project-specific\, or obfuscated. Developers may even label code with a given pattern name despite incorrect implementations. In such cases\, an LLM that relies on names can become confidently wrong. Conversely\, if code is already clean and explicity annotated with the correct pattern name\, the detection model may not really be needed. In both scenarios\, reliance on identifier names may defeat the purpose of design pattern detection. We conduct a study based on five LLM encoders and a dataset containing 1300 design-pattern instances collected from 214 Java projects to determine whether current LLM-based DPD genuinely learns structure or rely on name-based shortcuts. Our results show that models trained on raw code are dominated by identifier-driven attributions and suffer substantial performance degradation when tested on code with different identifier names. We also find that code anonymisation replacing identifier names by randomly set names increases reliance on code structure but does not fully eliminate identifier dependence\, leaving a residual robustness gap under out-of-sample naming conventions. This study highlights the importance of understanding the features learned by LLMs before adopting them in practice.\n
LOCATION:MB 3.430 - 1450 Guy St, Montreal, Quebec H3H 0A1, Montreal, Canada
LAST-MODIFIED:20260602T205645Z
END:VEVENT
