UID:2b41f05c-ac61-4fba-ba17-53c44e36dd67@conf.researchr.org
CREATED:20260520T220524Z
SUMMARY:[FSE Research Papers] CI/CD Configuration Practices in Open-Source Android Apps: An Empirical Study - Taher A. Ghaleb\, Osamah Abduljalil\, Safwat Hassan
DESCRIPTION:\textbf{\textit{Background.}} Continuous Integration and Continuous Delivery (CI/CD) automates the building\, testing\, packaging\, and deployment of software systems. In mobile app development\, particularly for Android apps\, CI/CD pipelines must accommodate platform-specific build tools and support reliable building\, rigorous testing\, packaging\, and proper releasing processes. These requirements introduce additional configuration and maintenance considerations compared to many other software domains.\n\textbf{\textit{Motivation.}} Despite the availability of multiple CI/CD services\, there is limited empirical evidence on how Android projects configure and evolve their pipelines\, how complex these configurations are\, and what drives their maintenance activities. A systematic understanding of these aspects is necessary to identify challenges\, inefficiencies\, and opportunities to improve CI/CD adoption in mobile development.\n\textbf{\textit{Approach.}} We conducted a large-scale empirical study of 2\,557 open-source Android apps using four major CI/CD services: \textit{GitHub Actions}\,\textit{ Travis CI}\, \textit{CircleCI}\, and \textit{GitLab CI/CD}. We examined 4\,295 YAML configuration files containing 24\,976 directives. We addressed three research questions addressing (RQ1) configuration complexity\, heterogeneity\, and tool usage\, (RQ2) the evolution of CI/CD configurations over time\, and (RQ3) recurring themes in CI/CD maintenance. We also performed a thematic analysis of 384 commit messages and validated results using Latent Dirichlet Allocation (LDA) across the full commit data.\n\textbf{\textit{Findings.}} We observe substantial variation in configuration complexity across CI/CD services and programming languages\, along with a lack of standardization. More than 81% of configuration effort is devoted to setup and initialization tasks. Only about half of the projects implement automated testing\, predominantly standard unit tests via Gradle\, and just 9% support deployment automation. When present\, deployment rarely targets app stores directly\; most projects rely on third-party tools or manual processes. CI/CD pipelines change approximately every two months on average\, and maintenance frequency correlates positively with active issue tracking\, project size and age\, and community engagement. We identify 11 recurring maintenance themes: over one-third focus on workflow improvements and build fixing\, while another third address updates to build environments\, tools\, and dependencies\, partially automated by bots such as Dependabot and Renovate.\n\textbf{\textit{Implications.}} Our results highlight the need for greater standardization in Android CI/CD practices and reveal significant opportunities to reduce configuration overhead. The findings motivate the development of AI-powered and automated tooling to streamline setup\, strengthen testing and deployment automation\, and lower barriers to effective CI/CD adoption in mobile software engineering.\n
LOCATION:MB 2.435 - 1450 Guy St, Montreal, Quebec H3H 0A1, Montreal, Canada
LAST-MODIFIED:20260520T221447Z
END:VEVENT
BEGIN:VEVENT
