SUMMARY:[FSE Research Papers] Persona-Conditioned LLM Interaction for Software Engineering Education (Extended Abstract) - Mohamad Kassab\, Sulav G. Shrestha
DESCRIPTION:Generative large language models (LLMs) are widely used by software engineering (SE) students\, yet mainstream chat interfaces provide generic explanations that are weakly aligned with SE discourse and just-in-time help seeking. We present a speech-to-speech educational tool that routes learner questions to an appropriate SE expert persona and generates concise\, persona-conditioned explanations. In a controlled\, formative within-subjects pilot study with 24 junior-level SE students\, we compare the tool against the publicly available ChatGPT interface. The persona-conditioned system was rated higher for engagement (M=4.46 vs. 3.46) and perceived usefulness (M=4.13 vs. 3.75)\, with a smaller gain in perceived understanding (M=3.92 vs. 3.71). Short-term factual recall did not differ (6.92/8 vs. 6.63/8)\, and 79% of participants preferred the persona-based tool. These findings suggest that interaction framing can improve learners’ experience without measurable short-term recall gains\, motivating longitudinal classroom studies and instructor-configurable controls for responsible adoption.\n
LOCATION:MB 9C - 1450 Guy St, Montreal, Quebec H3H 0A1, Montreal, Canada
LAST-MODIFIED:20260522T213459Z
END:VEVENT
BEGIN:VEVENT
DTSTART:20260708T155000Z
DTEND:20260708T160000Z
DTSTAMP:20260625T155152Z
UID:9a46ff0d-7d47-4e52-96d4-533673d2c030@conf.researchr.org
CREATED:20260520T224008Z
SUMMARY:[FSE Research Papers] Beyond Text: Understanding How Multimodal Generative AI Impacts Students Learning Software Development (Extended Abstract) - Huayu Liang\, Chris Brown
DESCRIPTION:Recent advances in multimodal generative AI (GenAI) extend student support beyond text-focused prompting to include audio dialogue\, media upload\, and real-time stream (\ i.e.\, live screen-sharing). Yet\, the educational implications of these multimodal capabilities in software engineering (SE) development settings remain underexplored. This extended abstract presents a proposed study to investigate how students leverage multimodal GenAI while completing realistic SE tasks in an open-source software (OSS) workflow\, and how multimodal interaction shapes task-solving processes and outcomes. We will conduct in-person think-aloud sessions (min. n = 25) in which participants use a multimodal GenAI tool (Google AI Studio) across interaction modes while working through bug fixing\, feature implementation with pull request contribution\, and test writing tasks. We will triangulate screen/audio recordings\, interaction traces\, and pre/post surveys to characterize modality selection and prompting strategies\, assess participants’ usage patterns\, and explore impacts on efficiency and solution accuracy. Essentially\, the study aims to provide insights for CS/SE educators and tool designers on when multimodal GenAI support is beneficial\, when it adds overhead\, and how to scaffold its use to promote robust learning and practical skill development.\n
LOCATION:MB 9C - 1450 Guy St, Montreal, Quebec H3H 0A1, Montreal, Canada
LAST-MODIFIED:20260522T213511Z
END:VEVENT
BEGIN:VEVENT
DTSTART:20260708T160000Z
DTEND:20260708T161000Z
DTSTAMP:20260625T155152Z
UID:24f335ae-eb3f-47a5-bdc4-864221cd1d53@conf.researchr.org
CREATED:20260520T224008Z
SUMMARY:[FSE Research Papers] Pragmatic Use of Generative AI in an Introductory Programming Course (extended abstract) - Thomas Overklift\, Andy Zaidman
DESCRIPTION:This paper introduces and discusses an early intervention of Generative AI (GenAI) in a first year university-level introductory programming course of a Computer Science programme. In our quest to convince our critical student audience that deep knowledge and understanding of programming is still relevant\, and not everything can be vibe coded\, we designed 3 interventions that we deployed at the start\, around the middle\, and towards the end of the course. From interactions with students\, it made it clear that they were surprised at some mistakes that GenAI solutions contained. For us teachers\, it solidified the idea that we should keep teaching student in-depth programming knowledge and understanding.\n
LOCATION:MB 9C - 1450 Guy St, Montreal, Quebec H3H 0A1, Montreal, Canada
LAST-MODIFIED:20260522T213521Z
END:VEVENT
BEGIN:VEVENT
DTSTART:20260708T161000Z
DTEND:20260708T162000Z
DTSTAMP:20260625T155152Z
UID:d3c37abd-dbf4-48fd-9b07-f5b4315f8a96@conf.researchr.org
CREATED:20260520T224008Z
SUMMARY:[FSE Research Papers] Refactoria: A Game-Based Tool for Learning Code Refactoring - Eman Abdullah AlOmar\, David Van Hise\, Stephen Pachucki\, Nerissa Lundquist\, Christopher Engelbart
DESCRIPTION:Refactoring is a crucial practice in software maintenance\, that aims at improving coding practices while addressing design flaws. Due to the importance of the topic\, several methods and strategies have been proposed for teaching and training refactoring\, including interactive learning\, incremental learning\, gamification\, visualization\, experimentation\, and e-activity planning. However\, the skills needed to identify and refactor code smells come from training and experience\, and the lack of motivation may hinder developers in the adoption of refactoring tools. In this paper\, we aim at developing Refactoria\, an innovative game-based learning environment that supports the acquisition of code smell and refactoring concepts through interactive gameplay. The players play as an expert chef with their sidekick Watson the Whiskbot to refactor Watson’s instructions into efficient\, readable\, and easily maintainable code. We present an experiment with 24 student developers. In particular\, we study the perception\, effectiveness\, and usefulness of gamification to engage developers in code smell identification and refactoring. Our results show that the game is effective in teaching developers code smell and refactoring concepts. In light of our findings\, we believe that Refactoria contributes a unique blend of pedagogical innovation and practical relevance.\n
LOCATION:MB 9C - 1450 Guy St, Montreal, Quebec H3H 0A1, Montreal, Canada
LAST-MODIFIED:20260522T213527Z
END:VEVENT
BEGIN:VEVENT
DTSTART:20260708T162000Z
DTEND:20260708T163000Z
DTSTAMP:20260625T155152Z
UID:ff454c16-b009-4e00-8eb6-fb865e333b63@conf.researchr.org
CREATED:20260520T224008Z
SUMMARY:[FSE Research Papers] Extended Abstract of Enabling Emotion-Aware Collaboration in Capstone Projects - Wardah Naeem Awan\, Maria Paasivaara
DESCRIPTION:Emotions play a central role in shaping collaboration\, motivation\, and learning during software engineering capstone projects\, yet they are rarely surfaced or systematically reflected upon in team practices. This paper introduces a lightweight\, theory-informed framework for embedding emotional awareness into Scrum retrospectives. The framework consists of five phases: Sense\, Share\, Interpret\, Respond\, and Monitor. It guides students through individual and team-based emotional reflection. Drawing on Control–Value Theory (CVT) and Socially Shared Regulation of Learning (SSRL)\, the approach encourages teams to identify emotional patterns\, discuss triggers\, plan small adjustments\, and maintain awareness over time. Designed to fit within standard Scrum practices\, the framework requires no additional tools and supports emotionally reflective collaboration without disrupting workflow. We plan to evaluate the framework in a six-sprint capstone course involving 72 students\, with the goal of exploring its feasibility and potential to enhance team learning and emotional regulation in educational settings.\n
LOCATION:MB 9C - 1450 Guy St, Montreal, Quebec H3H 0A1, Montreal, Canada
LAST-MODIFIED:20260522T213534Z
END:VEVENT
